<HEADLINE>
<P>
ALLAN MALAMUD: NOTES ON A SCORECARD 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By ALLAN MALAMUD 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 What does the well-dressed football player wear? . . .  
</P>
<P>
 If he is a Ram, it is a replica of the uniform worn by the 1951 team that 
remains the only one in Los Angeles franchise history to have won an NFL title. 
. . .  
</P>
<P>
 The gold jerseys, blue numerals, and white pants will make a return appearance 
Sunday for the game against the San Francisco 49ers at Anaheim Stadium. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Now, if the Rams can only flash some of that 1951 form. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 The offense was one of the most exciting ever, averaging 32 points and 
featuring the passing of Norm Van Brocklin and Bob Waterfield, the receiving of 
Elroy (Crazylegs) Hirsch and Tom Fears, and the rushing of the Bull Elephant 
backfield of Deacon Dan Towler, Tank Younger and Dick Hoerner. . . . Van 
Brocklin completed 100 of 194 passes for 1,725 yards and 13 touchdowns. 
Waterfield completed 88 of 176 for 1,566 yards and 13 touchdowns. The league 
passing championship in those days was determined by yards per attempt. 
Champion Waterfield edged runner-up Van Brocklin, 8.90 to 8.89. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 No wonder there was a quarterback controversy. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Coach Joe Stydahar's team went 8-4 to win the National Conference title and 
then defeated the American Conference champion Cleveland Browns, 24-17, in the 
NFL title game before 57,522 at the Coliseum. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 That's right, postseason play consisted of exactly one game. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Most distinctive about the uniform, which will be worn again as part of the 
league's 75th anniversary celebration, were the Rams' horns on the helmet. . . 
.  
</P>
<P>
 One night during the 1948 season, running back Fred Gehrke, who had been an 
art major in college, went home and painted horns on what he thought was an 
uninteresting piece of headgear. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 His teammates approved of the new look and the design has remained to this 
day. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Gehrke will be one of Georgia Frontiere's guests Sunday along with former Rams 
Hirsch, Fears, Towler, Younger, Hoerner, Don Paul, Howard (Red) Hickey, Henry 
Thompson, Woodley Lewis, Bob Boyd, Stan West and Jim Benton and former general 
manager Tex Schramm. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 Benton set an NFL one-game record for receiving yardage -- 303 against the 
Detroit Lions in 1945 -- that wasn't broken until 40 years later by Stephone 
Paige of the Kansas City Chiefs. . . . The current record holder is the Rams' 
Flipper Anderson, who caught passes for 336 yards against New Orleans on Nov. 
26, 1989, and would settle for a fraction of that Sunday against the 49ers. . . 
.  
</P>
<P>
 * 
</P>
<P>
 It should come as absolutely no surprise that UCLA will be playing in 
September against a Nebraska team that is ranked first in one poll and second 
in the other. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 In 1983, the Bruins lost to 
</P>
<P>
 No. 1 Nebraska on Sept. 24 at Lincoln, 42-10. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 In 1984, the Bruins lost to 
</P>
<P>
 No. 1 Nebraska on Sept. 22 at the Rose Bowl, 42-3. . . . 
</P>
<P>
 In 1987, the Bruins lost to 
</P>
<P>
 No. 2 Nebraska on Sept. 12 at Lincoln, 42-33. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 In 1988, the Bruins beat No. 2 Nebraska on Sept. 10 at the Rose Bowl, 41-28. . 
. .  
</P>
<P>
 Last Sept. 18, the Cornhuskers were ranked a lowly eighth when they beat the 
Bruins at the Rose Bowl, 14-13. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 It's terrible how television can dictate the starting times of football games. 
Prime Ticket has decided to televise the USC-Baylor game Sept. 24 at the 
Coliseum, meaning a change was made Monday on the kickoff time from 12:30 p.m. 
to 7 p.m. What about the fan who had shelled out good money for tickets and 
made plans for that evening? . . .  
</P>
<P>
 You could have watched live college football on the tube nonstop from 9 a.m. 
Saturday to 1 a.m. Sunday. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 John Elway was 15-18 as a starting quarterback at Stanford. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Those two touchdown catches against the Philadelphia Eagles on Monday might 
start turning it around for former Trojan Curtis Conway, who has been a 
disappointment with the Chicago Bears. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Maybe putting William Perry in the backfield would solve the Eagles' short 
yardage-for-a-touchdown rushing problems. The Fridge has experience, you know. 
. . .  
</P>
<P>
 If Julio Cesar Chavez beats Meldrick Taylor and Frankie Randall defeats Juan 
Coggi as expected Saturday night, Chavez and Randall will be rematched Dec. 10. 
. . .  
</P>
<P>
 The two best of the six title fights on the MGM Grand card should be World 
Boxing Council super featherweight champion James Leija vs. Gabriel Ruelas and 
International Boxing Federation welterweight champion Felix Trinidad vs. Yory 
Boy Campas. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 Those four fighters have a combined record of 145-2-2. . . .  
</P>
<P>
 The new heavyweight sensation is Michael Nunn, who weighed 195 pounds the 
other night. . . . I wonder what the Dodgers' magic number is. 
</P>
