<TYPE>
<P>
Wild Art 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091494-0027 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 078875 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
September 14, 1994, Wednesday, Home Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Sports; Part C; Page 8; Column 1; Sports Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
132 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
SAILING; DORESTE MAKES A STRONG MOVE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By RICH ROBERTS 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Jose Luis Doreste of Spain, who helped to win two Star class world 
championships as crew for Antonio Gorostegui in 1982 and '83, made his best 
move toward winning one as skipper by finishing first in Tuesday's third race 
of the 73rd Star worlds at San Diego. 
</P>
<P>
 Doreste was still far off the lead halfway through the event, having placed 
29th and 30th in the first two races because, he said, "I was not 
inspired.(Those were) the most difficult races I have ever done." 
</P>
<P>
 Canada's Ross MacDonald, who won the second race, remained the overall leader 
after finishing seventh Tuesday. San Francisco's John Kostecki was third with 
placings of 1-9-4.  
</P>
<P>
 The Etchells world championship at Newport Beach had a lay day Tuesday. Both 
competitions are scheduled to conclude Friday. RICH ROBERTS 
</P>
</TEXT>
