<HEADLINE>
<P>
GLENDALE / BURBANK FOCUS: GLENDALE; FUND-RAISERS SLATED TO AID ARDEN HOUSE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By TONY OLIVO 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Verdugo Mental Health Center's  
</P>
<P>
 Arden House, a Glendale day-rehabilitation program for those suffering from 
schizophrenia, anxiety disorders or severe depression, will hold two 
fund-raisers this week to supplement a limited government-subsidized budget. 
</P>
<P>
 The first event, a dinner benefit at a local Sizzler Steak Restaurant, is 
tonight. 
</P>
<P>
 The second will be a square dance at St. Barnabas Episcopal Church in Eagle 
Rock on Sunday afternoon. 
</P>
<P>
 The Arden House exists through state funds provided by the Los Angeles County 
Department of Mental Health.  
</P>
<P>
 The program helps people with mental illnesses by offering them safety lessons 
on how to avoid being victimized, field trips, arts and crafts classes and 
general group and individual therapy sessions. 
</P>
<P>
 In a "clubhouse" setting, Arden House members attend sessions three times a 
week, choosing activities that best suit their needs.  
</P>
<P>
 Tonight's dinner will be from 5 to 8 p.m. at the restaurant at 1544 Canada 
Blvd. 
</P>
<P>
 The $8.50 admission includes an entree and salad bar. 
</P>
<P>
 The square dance Sunday will be from 1 to 5 p.m. in the church at 2109 
Chicksaw Ave.  
</P>
<P>
 Tickets to this event are $4.  
</P>
<P>
 For further information, call (818) 246-5756. TONY OLIVO 
</P>
</TEXT>
<TYPE>
<P>
Column; Brief 
</P>
</TYPE>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091494-0043 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 078891 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
September 14, 1994, Wednesday, Orange County Edition 
</P>
</DATE>
<SECTION>
<P>
Metro; Part B; Page 8; Column 4; Op-Ed Desk 
</P>
</SECTION>
<LENGTH>
<P>
206 words 
</P>
</LENGTH>
<HEADLINE>
<P>
FUNDING FOR SCHOOLS 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 * As our children returned to school last week, many of them entered aging 
facilities needing repair, upgrade and improvement. Most of them sat in classes 
with over 30, often close to 40, peers.In many places around the state, class 
was held in "temporary" trailers disguised as classrooms. 
</P>
<P>
 With the slim defeat of the June bond proposition and the state Legislature's 
failure to place a new, smaller request before the voters in November, the 
facilities are guaranteed to get older, class sizes larger, and the "temporary" 
trailers won't be leaving. 
</P>
<P>
 For the fastest growing districts in Orange County, the short-term impact is 
that 13 building projects worth about $60 million are indefinitely on hold. In 
the longer term, Santa Ana Unified School District alone needs 15 new schools 
plus expansions and maintenance of existing schools. It is estimated that $6 
billion worth of new classrooms are needed statewide. 
</P>
<P>
 The entire issue of school funding needs to be reviewed and replaced with a 
rational system. The question is how long are we going to wait before we insist 
that all of our children have proper school facilities without regard to a 
Beverly Hills, 90210, or a Santa Ana, 92701, address? 
</P>
<P>
 MARK PEREW 
</P>
<P>
 Santa Ana 
</P>
</TEXT>
