<HEADLINE>
<P>
TMI TRANSFERS INVESTORS' SUIT FROM O.C. TO L.A. FEDERAL COURT 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By DEBORA VRANA, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Lawyers for Teachers Management & Investment Corp. said Tuesday they have 
transferred a lawsuit filed against the Newport Beach investment fund from 
Orange County to U.S. District Court in Los Angeles. 
</P>
<P>
 Four investors sued the 26-year-old fund on Aug. 23 in Orange County Superior 
Court alleging that its operators lost $100 million of client funds through 
fraud and racketeering.The suit seeks appointment of a receiver, alleging that 
TMI, which marketed real estate investments to teachers across California, is 
now insolvent. 
</P>
<P>
 Company owners Maurice B. Shuman and James R. Martin, who have denied the 
allegations, maintain that the downturn in the real estate market is 
responsible for the losses. 
</P>
<P>
 A hearing on whether to appoint a receiver for the company had been scheduled 
for next Monday. 
</P>
<P>
 "There probably won't be a hearing then," said David Grant, partner with Grant 
& Laubscher), the Irvine law firm representing TMI. 
</P>
<P>
 Grant said TMI wanted the suit moved because federal courts are generally 
better suited to "manage the complex issues involved in the lawsuit, including 
TMI's efforts to put the issues to either a vote of the limited partners or 
arbitration." 
</P>
<P>
 The lawyer for investors called the move by TMI a "judge-shopping" ploy. "They 
can try and pick whatever judge they want, but the day of justice will come," 
said Ron Rus, who represents the plaintiffs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> LA091494-0196 </DOCNO>
<DOCID> 079064 </DOCID>
<SOURCE>
<P>
 Los Angeles Times 
</P>
</SOURCE>
<DATE>
<P>
September 14, 1994, Wednesday, Orange County Edition 
