<HEADLINE>
<P>
PERES, ARAFAT RESOLVE THORNY AID ISSUE IN OSLO 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By Associated Press 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Israeli Foreign Minister Shimon Peres and Palestine Liberation Organization 
Chairman Yasser Arafat resolved the thorny issue of development aid for the 
Palestinian territories Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
 After an afternoon of talks in Oslo, where both men came to mark the one-year 
anniversary of the Mideast peace accord, Israeli negotiators said that Arafat 
had agreed to drop the demand to address Jerusalem's status as part of an aid 
package, according to a preliminary draft of their final statement. 
</P>
<P>
 Peres and Arafat were meeting privately and with Norwegian and U.N. officials 
to discuss, among other things, $2.3 billion in development aid for the 
Palestinian territories. 
</P>
</TEXT>
