From Times Staff and Wire Reports 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 With encouragement from President Clinton, congressional Democratic leaders 
are initiating eleventh-hour discussions with their GOP counterparts to see if 
a modest first step toward health care reform can be salvaged before Congress 
goes home next month, House Speaker Thomas S. Foley (D-Wash.) said. "We are 
going to explore that in both the House and in the Senate, Foley said.He did 
not detail the reforms he has in mind but references to "incremental" measures 
made by Foley generally have meant a series of limited insurance reforms that 
make it easier to buy coverage, especially for those who have some existing 
medical condition. But one influential GOP senator, Phil Gramm of Texas, said, 
"I think it's a bad idea to try to bring this debate back to life." 
